Question:
Given a list of string lists, flatten them into a single list.

Input:
List<List<String>> list = Arrays.asList(Arrays.asList("a", "b"), Arrays.asList("c", "d"));

Solution:

Java 8 Streams flatten nested List<String> using flatMap(List::stream). For input [["a", "b"], ["c", "d"]], produces flat ["a", "b", "c", "d"].

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream outer list via stream(). Apply flatMap(innerList -> innerList.stream()) to map each inner list to its stream and flatten. Collect to new List<String> with Collectors.toList().

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class FlattenNestedLists {
    public static List<String> flatten(List<List<String>> nested) {
        return nested.stream()
                     .flatMap(List::stream)
                     .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<List<String>> list = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList("a", "b"), 
            Arrays.asList("c", "d")
        );
        List<String> flat = flatten(list);
        System.out.println(flat);  // [a, b, c, d]
    }
}

Method reference List::stream concise; preserves encounter order.
â€‹

#Thought Process
flatMap applies function returning Stream, flattening nested streams into one. List::stream perfect mapper for inner lists. collect(toList()) gathers result. Avoids nested loops declaratively.

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty outer: Returns [].
Outer with empty inners: [].
Null outer: NPE on stream().
Null inner list: null.stream() NPE; filter out.
Null elements in inners: Preserved in flat.
Uneven inners: All concatenated.
